sed of the Celtic elements <i>domno-</i> ‘world’ + <i>val-</i> ‘might, rule’. Compare the Anglicized form   Donald   and the Scottish clan name   McDonald  .","History: The O'Donnells, like the O'Neills (see   O'Neill  ), claim descent from Niall of the Nine Hostages (Niall Noígíallach), a legendary 5th-century king of Ireland. Their traditional base is Tyrconnell (i.e. Donegal)."],"variants":[{"name":"O'Donell","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Donnell  ."]},{"name":"O'Donnel","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Donnell  ."]},{"name":"O'Daniel","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Donnell  , influenced by the Biblical name   Daniel  , to which it is etymologically unrelated."]},{"name":"O'Donald","meanings":["Irish: Scotticized form of   O'Donnell  . The Irish personal name <i>Domhnall</i> was Latinized as <i>Donaldus</i>, which is the source of <i>Donald</i>, the form of the personal name used in English in Scotland, though not in Ireland. The form <i>O'Donald</i> is therefore a 19th-century hybrid. Compare   Donald  ."]},{"name":"Donald","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   McDonald   (<i>Mac Dhomhnaill</i>), from the Gaelic personal name <i>Domhnall</i>; found in 13th- and 14th-century Scotland as <i>Dofnald</i>, <i>Douenald</i>, <i>Dufenald</i>, and <i>Donald</i>.","Irish (Ulster): possibly also a shortened and altered form of Irish   O'Donell  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John O'Donnell was born in 1338. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs. John O'Donnell."},"et":{"Cir 1338–Deceased":"1338–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1360–1397":"1360–1397","1338–Male":"1338–Surnud","1338":"1338",